# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: WarriorPath | Scene: WarriorRahayal3
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah woke early the next morning to a servant knocking on her door."
    new "Sarah woke early the next morning to a servant knocking on her door."

    old "She and Lady Carolyn had been summoned to Gilead's Estate for their meeting."
    new "She and Lady Carolyn had been summoned to Gilead's Estate for their meeting."

    old "Sarah had quickly finished getting dressed and Lady Carolyn had already been waiting for her."
    new "Sarah had quickly finished getting dressed and Lady Carolyn had already been waiting for her."

    old "Together they entered a carriage that was already waiting for them."
    new "Together they entered a carriage that was already waiting for them."

    old "Lady Carolyn had prepared for years in advance of this moment. It was no surprise that she was ready."
    new "Lady Carolyn had prepared for years in advance of this moment. It was no surprise that she was ready."

    old "As the horses began to pull the carriage, Sarah could hear the wooden wheels clattering against the cobblestone of the city streets."
    new "As the horses began to pull the carriage, Sarah could hear the wooden wheels clattering against the cobblestone of the city streets."

    old "They soon left Carolyn's estate behind, riding through the streets of Rahayal."
    new "They soon left Carolyn's estate behind, riding through the streets of Rahayal."

    old "Looking out of the window, Sarah saw the city pass by her."
    new "Looking out of the window, Sarah saw the city pass by her."

    old "At any other time in her life, she would have stared at the city in wonder. There was no city like it in all the world."
    new "At any other time in her life, she would have stared at the city in wonder. There was no city like it in all the world."

    old "But today, her thoughts were otherwise occupied."
    new "But today, her thoughts were otherwise occupied."

    old "Nervous?"
    new "Nervous?"

    old "Sarah was snapped from her thoughts by Carolyn's comment."
    new "Sarah was snapped from her thoughts by Carolyn's comment."

    old "What? Oh, no...not nervous."
    new "What? Oh, no...not nervous."

    old "Just contemplative, then?"
    new "Just contemplative, then?"

    old "Sarah watched out of the window again. It was early, but the streets were already begining to fill up."
    new "Sarah watched out of the window again. It was early, but the streets were already begining to fill up."

    old "I guess...perhaps I still don't quite know what to say when I meet this Gilead."
    new "I guess...perhaps I still don't quite know what to say when I meet this Gilead."

    old "You will know when we are there."
    new "You will know when we are there."

    old "Just look at you. You've managed to make your way through this world all on your own for years now."
    new "Just look at you. You've managed to make your way through this world all on your own for years now."

    old "Yes...but this is different."
    new "Yes...but this is different."

    old "Because this isn't about me surviving."
    new "Because this isn't about me surviving."

    old "It's about deciding if I want to take this man's help."
    new "It's about deciding if I want to take this man's help."

    old "She saw Carolyn look at her, calm, yet intense."
    new "She saw Carolyn look at her, calm, yet intense."

    old "His Legions will secure your victory, remember that."
    new "His Legions will secure your victory, remember that."

    old "I know that. But at what price?"
    new "I know that. But at what price?"

    old "And who is to say that I should seek this victory at all?"
    new "And who is to say that I should seek this victory at all?"

    old "Lady Carolyn kept looking directly at her."
    new "Lady Carolyn kept looking directly at her."

    old "Are you in doubt?"
    new "Are you in doubt?"

    old "Sarah looked out the window again."
    new "Sarah looked out the window again."

    old "It's not doubt...it's just...how many will die if I say yes to this plan?"
    new "It's not doubt...it's just...how many will die if I say yes to this plan?"

    old "All for what? To put myself in back on the throne?"
    new "All for what? To put myself in back on the throne?"

    old "I understand that you are hesitant."
    new "I understand that you are hesitant."

    old "Your Father was much the same."
    new "Your Father was much the same."

    old "He was?"
    new "He was?"

    old "I've met my fair share of Nobles, Kings and even an Emperor."
    new "I've met my fair share of Nobles, Kings and even an Emperor."

    old "At best, they were thoughtless of the lives beneath them. At worst, they eagerly spend them."
    new "At best, they were thoughtless of the lives beneath them. At worst, they eagerly spend them."

    old "It was only the rare few who truly weighed the lives they held in their hands."
    new "It was only the rare few who truly weighed the lives they held in their hands."

    old "Lady Carolyn leaned forward and placed her hand on Sarah's leg."
    new "Lady Carolyn leaned forward and placed her hand on Sarah's leg."

    old "Your Father was one such man. And I think you are forged from the same steel as he was."
    new "Your Father was one such man. And I think you are forged from the same steel as he was."

    old "Sarah felt her mind, rushed with memories of her father, so long repressed."
    new "Sarah felt her mind, rushed with memories of her father, so long repressed."

    old "Could she ever hope to be half the ruler he was?"
    new "Could she ever hope to be half the ruler he was?"

    old "But while great rulers must properly weigh each life, they also cannot allow themselves to be paralyzed by fear."
    new "But while great rulers must properly weigh each life, they also cannot allow themselves to be paralyzed by fear."

    old "A truly great ruler, understanding the cost, will still do what must be done."
    new "A truly great ruler, understanding the cost, will still do what must be done."

    old "And yes..."
    new "And yes..."

    old "Lady Carolyn was quiet for a moment."
    new "Lady Carolyn was quiet for a moment."

    old "This will mean it will weigh heavier on your heart than it will on those foolish rulers who spend lives without thought."
    new "This will mean it will weigh heavier on your heart than it will on those foolish rulers who spend lives without thought."

    old "But you must still do it."
    new "But you must still do it."

    old "Why? So I can sit on a throne?"
    new "Why? So I can sit on a throne?"

    old "No. If this was all for vanity or greed, you would not be here."
    new "No. If this was all for vanity or greed, you would not be here."

    old "It is because you know as well as any other, the good you can do from that throne."
    new "It is because you know as well as any other, the good you can do from that throne."

    old "And that right now, your own people, languish under the heel of tyrants. Barbarians."
    new "And that right now, your own people, languish under the heel of tyrants. Barbarians."

    old "Sarah felt Carolyn squeeze her leg."
    new "Sarah felt Carolyn squeeze her leg."

    old "There are countless from Rosanna here, refugees. There are countless more, scattered across the world."
    new "There are countless from Rosanna here, refugees. There are countless more, scattered across the world."

    old "But they are few in numbers compared to those who are still left behind. Trapped and at the mercy of the Tribes."
    new "But they are few in numbers compared to those who are still left behind. Trapped and at the mercy of the Tribes."

    old "Sarah saw the pain on Carolyn's expression. It was rare to see such emotion on her face."
    new "Sarah saw the pain on Carolyn's expression. It was rare to see such emotion on her face."

    old "I can tell you stories, gathered by my spies that remain behind in Rosanna."
    new "I can tell you stories, gathered by my spies that remain behind in Rosanna."

    old "I have entire cabinets, filled with reports, one atrocity after the other, would you want me to have them send to you."
    new "I have entire cabinets, filled with reports, one atrocity after the other, would you want me to have them send to you."

    old "Then you must act."
    new "Then you must act."

    old "For there is nobody else who can do it. Nobody else who cause and claim is as clear as yours."
    new "For there is nobody else who can do it. Nobody else who cause and claim is as clear as yours."

    old "Lady Carolyn leaned back."
    new "Lady Carolyn leaned back."

    old "I will not force your hand on the matter of Gilead, though I will advise you that I believe we will need his Legions."
    new "I will not force your hand on the matter of Gilead, though I will advise you that I believe we will need his Legions."

    old "But you must take charge of the refugees of Rosanna and lead them back home."
    new "But you must take charge of the refugees of Rosanna and lead them back home."

    old "Under your banner, they will fight as hard as they must, and we can drive out the remnants of the Tribes that plague our lands."
    new "Under your banner, they will fight as hard as they must, and we can drive out the remnants of the Tribes that plague our lands."

    old "Looking out of the window, Sarah saw the carriage roll along the streets."
    new "Looking out of the window, Sarah saw the carriage roll along the streets."

    old "Here, in this capital, the notions of war seemed so far away."
    new "Here, in this capital, the notions of war seemed so far away."

    old "But at her word, she would unleash a war. At her word, thousands would die."
    new "But at her word, she would unleash a war. At her word, thousands would die."

    old "And those who die?"
    new "And those who die?"

    old "They will die good deaths."
    new "They will die good deaths."

    old "Wish that we could all be so fortunate."
    new "Wish that we could all be so fortunate."

    old "They rode the rest of their trip in silence."
    new "They rode the rest of their trip in silence."

    old "Their carriage pulled through the vast gates of Gilead's Estate."
    new "Their carriage pulled through the vast gates of Gilead's Estate."

    old "As soon as they arrived, servants rushed up and ushered them into the great Estate."
    new "As soon as they arrived, servants rushed up and ushered them into the great Estate."

    old "Carolyn's had been impressive, but this place was something altogether different."
    new "Carolyn's had been impressive, but this place was something altogether different."

    old "Even her home of Castle Reinmeer seemed small in contrast."
    new "Even her home of Castle Reinmeer seemed small in contrast."

    old "The servants brought them towards the great receiving hall, and then, just as suddenly they left."
    new "The servants brought them towards the great receiving hall, and then, just as suddenly they left."

    old "Sarah looked about."
    new "Sarah looked about."

    old "Where is he?"
    new "Where is he?"

    old "Gilead? Ooh, he'll show up in a moment."
    new "Gilead? Ooh, he'll show up in a moment."

    old "He likes to do things like this."
    new "He likes to do things like this."

    old "Make people wait?"
    new "Make people wait?"

    old "For as much as he has achieved in life he can be..."
    new "For as much as he has achieved in life he can be..."

    old "Carolyn looked about to make sure there was nobody else in the room."
    new "Carolyn looked about to make sure there was nobody else in the room."

    old "A petty man."
    new "A petty man."

    old "I can't say I've missed the days of playing political games."
    new "I can't say I've missed the days of playing political games."

    old "Say whatever you want about mercenaries, at least they're direct about how they feel."
    new "Say whatever you want about mercenaries, at least they're direct about how they feel."

    old "They might put a knife in your ribs, but they won't smile in your face as they do it."
    new "They might put a knife in your ribs, but they won't smile in your face as they do it."

    old "Carolyn softly laughed."
    new "Carolyn softly laughed."

    old "The years sure have changed you, Sarah."
    new "The years sure have changed you, Sarah."

    old "They sat together for what felt like nearly an hour, until finally, a great door opened up."
    new "They sat together for what felt like nearly an hour, until finally, a great door opened up."

    old "Two servants guided them through the door towards a great throne near the far end of the room."
    new "Two servants guided them through the door towards a great throne near the far end of the room."

    old "Sitting there, the man that could only be Gilead."
    new "Sitting there, the man that could only be Gilead."

    old "Sarah thought of him as a man, but his pale, unnatural skin made him appear anything but."
    new "Sarah thought of him as a man, but his pale, unnatural skin made him appear anything but."

    old "Some primal part of herself felt unnerved by the sight of it."
    new "Some primal part of herself felt unnerved by the sight of it."

    old "He remained seated as she approached."
    new "He remained seated as she approached."

    old "Lady Carolyn, always glad to receive you."
    new "Lady Carolyn, always glad to receive you."

    old "Lady Carolyn slightly bowed."
    new "Lady Carolyn slightly bowed."

    old "Lord Gilead, as always an honour and a great priviledge to be hosted by yourself."
    new "Lord Gilead, as always an honour and a great priviledge to be hosted by yourself."

    old "Carolyn gestured towards Sarah."
    new "Carolyn gestured towards Sarah."

    old "I have brought with me today the guest of whom I spoke."
    new "I have brought with me today the guest of whom I spoke."

    old "Princess Sarah Rose, heir to Rosanna."
    new "Princess Sarah Rose, heir to Rosanna."

    old "The words fell heavy, as did the silence that followed."
    new "The words fell heavy, as did the silence that followed."

    old "Sarah fell down to one knee."
    new "Sarah fell down to one knee."

    old "I was honored to receive your invitation, and to learn that a man of your stature has taken an interest in my cause."
    new "I was honored to receive your invitation, and to learn that a man of your stature has taken an interest in my cause."

    old "My people's cause."
    new "My people's cause."

    old "Her words lingered."
    new "Her words lingered."

    old "Sarah eyed the man named Gilead, waiting his next move."
    new "Sarah eyed the man named Gilead, waiting his next move."

    old "Please, stand up any friend of Carolyn is a friend of mine."
    new "Please, stand up any friend of Carolyn is a friend of mine."

    old "Sarah smiled. Soft pleasantries to start then."
    new "Sarah smiled. Soft pleasantries to start then."

    old "It warms my heart to hear such kind words. Thank you for so graciously receiving us."
    new "It warms my heart to hear such kind words. Thank you for so graciously receiving us."

    old "She had grown up in court, pretending the part of Princess until it came as second nature to her."
    new "She had grown up in court, pretending the part of Princess until it came as second nature to her."

    old "Even a lifetime of soldiering would not erase that."
    new "Even a lifetime of soldiering would not erase that."

    old "She watched as Gilead leaned back in his chair, appearing entirely comfortable. Almost disinterested."
    new "She watched as Gilead leaned back in his chair, appearing entirely comfortable. Almost disinterested."

    old "All of it was a game, Sarah knew that much."
    new "All of it was a game, Sarah knew that much."

    old "Lady Carolyn had told her how much was at stake for Gilead."
    new "Lady Carolyn had told her how much was at stake for Gilead."

    old "But a man like him would not be foolish enough to appear desperate."
    new "But a man like him would not be foolish enough to appear desperate."

    old "So, has our mutual friend told you about me?"
    new "So, has our mutual friend told you about me?"

    old "He gestured towards Lady Carolyn."
    new "He gestured towards Lady Carolyn."

    old "Yes, a little."
    new "Yes, a little."

    old "Only good things, I hope."
    new "Only good things, I hope."

    old "From what I've been made to understand, you are sympathetic to me cause."
    new "From what I've been made to understand, you are sympathetic to me cause."

    old "Your cause, yes."
    new "Your cause, yes."

    old "Though I must admit, until not so long ago, I was made to understand that you were one of the tragic casualties of the Tribes."
    new "Though I must admit, until not so long ago, I was made to understand that you were one of the tragic casualties of the Tribes."

    old "Sarah spread her arms out."
    new "Sarah spread her arms out."

    old "Most alive, I can assure you."
    new "Most alive, I can assure you."

    old "Yes, and the stories you must have."
    new "Yes, and the stories you must have."

    old "I would gladly wish to hear more."
    new "I would gladly wish to hear more."

    old "Gilead clapped his hands together, and a servant came rushing."
    new "Gilead clapped his hands together, and a servant came rushing."

    old "Yes, Master?"
    new "Yes, Master?"

    old "Please bring out something to eat for me and my dear guests."
    new "Please bring out something to eat for me and my dear guests."

    old "Right away, Master."
    new "Right away, Master."

    old "As quickly as the servant had appeared, so quickly was he now gone."
    new "As quickly as the servant had appeared, so quickly was he now gone."

    old "The food that Gilead had requested began to stream into the room almost immediately."
    new "The food that Gilead had requested began to stream into the room almost immediately."

    old "And the food seemed without end."
    new "And the food seemed without end."

    old "One servant after the other, serving up plate after plate."
    new "One servant after the other, serving up plate after plate."

    old "For a moment, Sarah imagined the table might give out."
    new "For a moment, Sarah imagined the table might give out."

    old "Everything in Rahayal was obscene in its scope, and this seemed no different. How much of it would be wasted, she thought."
    new "Everything in Rahayal was obscene in its scope, and this seemed no different. How much of it would be wasted, she thought."

    old "Together, all of them sat down at the table."
    new "Together, all of them sat down at the table."

    old "As I was saying, I am eager to learn more about you, Sarah."
    new "As I was saying, I am eager to learn more about you, Sarah."

    old "Carolyn here told me that she herself was equally surprised to find you alive."
    new "Carolyn here told me that she herself was equally surprised to find you alive."

    old "Yes, there are things in this world even Lady Carolyn does not know."
    new "Yes, there are things in this world even Lady Carolyn does not know."

    old "Only a few things, I promise."
    new "Only a few things, I promise."

    old "Sarah began to tell Gilead of her story."
    new "Sarah began to tell Gilead of her story."

    old "She could think of no better place to start than at the start."
    new "She could think of no better place to start than at the start."

    old "Her life in Rosanna, growing up at court. Her friend Kate. The betrayal. The invasion. Even Thomas."
    new "Her life in Rosanna, growing up at court. Her friend Kate. The betrayal. The invasion. Even Thomas."

    old "As Sarah recounted her life, she felt herself struck by the scope of it."
    new "As Sarah recounted her life, she felt herself struck by the scope of it."

    old "So much had happened since she was home...and now it had suddenly never been closer."
    new "So much had happened since she was home...and now it had suddenly never been closer."

    old "And that is how I find myself sitting here, making new friends."
    new "And that is how I find myself sitting here, making new friends."

    old "Gilead smiled as he looked from Sarah to Carolyn."
    new "Gilead smiled as he looked from Sarah to Carolyn."

    old "What a story."
    new "What a story."

    old "No just a Princess, but a warrior as well. Quite a potent combination."
    new "No just a Princess, but a warrior as well. Quite a potent combination."

    old "Gilead seemed pleased, almost as if he had to restrain himself."
    new "Gilead seemed pleased, almost as if he had to restrain himself."

    old "Just a woman, trying to survive."
    new "Just a woman, trying to survive."

    old "Sarah drank some of the wine, sweeter than anything she'd ever tasted."
    new "Sarah drank some of the wine, sweeter than anything she'd ever tasted."

    old "She wouldn't be surprised to learn that one cask of it was more expensive than a small house."
    new "She wouldn't be surprised to learn that one cask of it was more expensive than a small house."

    old "But what of yourself?"
    new "But what of yourself?"

    old "Gilead raised one eyebrow."
    new "Gilead raised one eyebrow."

    old "Carolyn has brought us together, praying we make good friends."
    new "Carolyn has brought us together, praying we make good friends."

    old "But I like to get to know my friend before...well, getting into bed with them, so to speak."
    new "But I like to get to know my friend before...well, getting into bed with them, so to speak."

    old "Gilead grinned, amused."
    new "Gilead grinned, amused."

    old "Yes, I suppose that is only fair after I asked you a thousand questions."
    new "Yes, I suppose that is only fair after I asked you a thousand questions."

    old "He leaned back."
    new "He leaned back."

    old "What do you want to know?"
    new "What do you want to know?"

    old "I told you all about how I ended up here at this table. I was wondering the same of yourself."
    new "I told you all about how I ended up here at this table. I was wondering the same of yourself."

    old "Well, I was born around three-hundred years ago."
    new "Well, I was born around three-hundred years ago."

    old "He said it as if it was an obvious, unremarkable thing."
    new "He said it as if it was an obvious, unremarkable thing."

    old "I know I don't look it, but such are the advantages of being crowned a Noctori."
    new "I know I don't look it, but such are the advantages of being crowned a Noctori."

    old "When I was born, the Mythran Empire was already flourshing. Had been for a few centuries at that point."
    new "When I was born, the Mythran Empire was already flourshing. Had been for a few centuries at that point."

    old "And though the family I was born to was wealthy enough, it wasn't a very impressive House."
    new "And though the family I was born to was wealthy enough, it wasn't a very impressive House."

    old "Most of the men in my family were expected to enter military service, the women the political core."
    new "Most of the men in my family were expected to enter military service, the women the political core."

    old "And so I joined the Mythran army."
    new "And so I joined the Mythran army."

    old "Gilead looked off into the distance, recalling memories."
    new "Gilead looked off into the distance, recalling memories."

    old "I was clever enough, had the right name and the connections, so I made Commander in time."
    new "I was clever enough, had the right name and the connections, so I made Commander in time."

    old "Like I said, a decent life, but in an Empire of millions, there are only a few hundred Noctori."
    new "Like I said, a decent life, but in an Empire of millions, there are only a few hundred Noctori."

    old "And everyone in Mythra with any ambition, strives for that select group."
    new "And everyone in Mythra with any ambition, strives for that select group."

    old "Yet here you are...clearly you succeeded."
    new "Yet here you are...clearly you succeeded."

    old "Yes, though I must admit that it was both a sliver of luck and timing."
    new "Yes, though I must admit that it was both a sliver of luck and timing."

    old "Well, though the number of Noctori fluctuates, it is always around the same number. A few more, a few less, but never by much."
    new "Well, though the number of Noctori fluctuates, it is always around the same number. A few more, a few less, but never by much."

    old "So the number of seats available are limited."
    new "So the number of seats available are limited."

    old "For one to enter into the Eternal Court, one must succeed yes, but there must also be failure."
    new "For one to enter into the Eternal Court, one must succeed yes, but there must also be failure."

    old "Failure?"
    new "Failure?"

    old "Yes. One of ambition that ascends, and one of the old and lazy that falls out of favor."
    new "Yes. One of ambition that ascends, and one of the old and lazy that falls out of favor."

    old "Favor. Sarah wonderd at the odd word. Favor with whom, she wondered."
    new "Favor. Sarah wonderd at the odd word. Favor with whom, she wondered."

    old "My luck was that the Empire was advancing on a great campaign in the Southern lands."
    new "My luck was that the Empire was advancing on a great campaign in the Southern lands."

    old "We were both greatly expanding, and at the same time, facing a constant attack from rebels in the newly conquered lands."
    new "We were both greatly expanding, and at the same time, facing a constant attack from rebels in the newly conquered lands."

    old "The campaign was led by a Noctori that was more occupied with looting the lands than properly subjugating them."
    new "The campaign was led by a Noctori that was more occupied with looting the lands than properly subjugating them."

    old "Gilead knocked his knuckles against the table."
    new "Gilead knocked his knuckles against the table."

    old "At that very same moment, the Orcish tribes, defeated but not yet broken, launched their last great raid on our Empire."
    new "At that very same moment, the Orcish tribes, defeated but not yet broken, launched their last great raid on our Empire."

    old "Everyone imagined the Orcs defeated, and so being posted to defend the Hyral Mountains was considered a posting of little renown."
    new "Everyone imagined the Orcs defeated, and so being posted to defend the Hyral Mountains was considered a posting of little renown."

    old "The kind of posting that a young man such as myself might be given."
    new "The kind of posting that a young man such as myself might be given."

    old "Unlike most of the others, I saw the Orcs for what they were, and I had prepared the forts under my command."
    new "Unlike most of the others, I saw the Orcs for what they were, and I had prepared the forts under my command."

    old "Their armies broke through nearly every defensive line we had...except for one."
    new "Their armies broke through nearly every defensive line we had...except for one."

    old "The Orcs went on a rampage. Looting, murdering, making slaves."
    new "The Orcs went on a rampage. Looting, murdering, making slaves."

    old "Had it not been for myself holding the line, they would have made it into the Empire's interior and done real damage."
    new "Had it not been for myself holding the line, they would have made it into the Empire's interior and done real damage."

    old "Instead, they now suffered a brief victory, followed by a crushing defeat at my hands."
    new "Instead, they now suffered a brief victory, followed by a crushing defeat at my hands."

    old "What happened after?"
    new "What happened after?"

    old "Well, after, I made sure to send my officers back to the capital of Rahayal."
    new "Well, after, I made sure to send my officers back to the capital of Rahayal."

    old "There they told the stories of what the Orcs had done in vivid detail."
    new "There they told the stories of what the Orcs had done in vivid detail."

    old "Before the week was over, I had become the hero of the Empire."
    new "Before the week was over, I had become the hero of the Empire."

    old "My rise was obvious."
    new "My rise was obvious."

    old "But, for every ascendant, another must fall."
    new "But, for every ascendant, another must fall."

    old "And so just as the stories of my victory began to spread, so too did the stories of one of the Noctori that lead the Southern Campaign."
    new "And so just as the stories of my victory began to spread, so too did the stories of one of the Noctori that lead the Southern Campaign."

    old "He had bragged for everyone to hear about the grand fortunes that he was bringing home to the capital."
    new "He had bragged for everyone to hear about the grand fortunes that he was bringing home to the capital."

    old "In any other moment, such loot would have made him a champion."
    new "In any other moment, such loot would have made him a champion."

    old "Now, the people instead saw him as a greedy fool who enriched himself as the flanks of the Empire were exposed to Orc raids."
    new "Now, the people instead saw him as a greedy fool who enriched himself as the flanks of the Empire were exposed to Orc raids."

    old "I fell into favor, and he fell out."
    new "I fell into favor, and he fell out."

    old "About a month later, I was summoned to the Eternal Court, and I was gifted the greatest blessing of all."
    new "About a month later, I was summoned to the Eternal Court, and I was gifted the greatest blessing of all."

    old "Ever since, I have been a dutiful member of the Eternal Court, tasked with offering a guiding and constant hand to the Empire."
    new "Ever since, I have been a dutiful member of the Eternal Court, tasked with offering a guiding and constant hand to the Empire."

    old "The position had clearly not done him poorly in terms of wealth either."
    new "The position had clearly not done him poorly in terms of wealth either."

    old "And how fortuitous that we might now have found one another."
